Anna Jagiellon last member of royal Jagiellon family died in 1596.↩
Bojt&lt;U+00E1&gt;r, 180&lt;U+2013&gt;186.↩
Translated as grand duke or grand prince. Kunigaik&lt;U+0161&gt;tis is a cognate of K&lt;U+00F6&gt;nig and king, and didysis magnifies it. See Rowell, 65-69, for the nature of didysis kunigaik&lt;U+0161&gt;tis in practice.↩
See Tadeusz Wasilewski in &quot;Przegl&lt;U+0105&gt;d Wschodni&quot; 1991 r., and Jan T&lt;U+0119&gt;gowski, Pierwsze pokolenia Giedyminowicz&lt;U+00F3&gt;w, Wroc&lt;U+0142&gt;aw–Pozna&lt;U+0144&gt; 1999, s. 124&lt;U+2013&gt;125↩
Stone, 4; In the late fourteenth century, ethnic Lithuanians are unlikely to have numbered more than 300,000, seven times fewer than the Christian Orthodox inhabitants. Lukowski and Zawadzki, 38&lt;U+2013&gt;9; The former Rus'ian principalities Polotsk, Vitebsk, Smolensk, Kiev, Volhynia, Podlasie, and Podolia retained the local laws and privileges they had enjoyed before coming under Lithuanian supremacy. Every new grand duke of Lithuania confirmed these privileges and promised not to submit the native populations to the Lithuanian court. Dvornik, 342; The Muscovite and Novgorod authors called Lithuanian Rus' territories &quot;The Lithuanian Land&quot;. Plokhy, 46↩
Bojt&lt;U+00E1&gt;r, 180.↩
Some historians, for example Vanda Sruogien&lt;U+0117&gt;-Sruoga in Jogaila (1350&lt;U+2013&gt;1434) and J.Deveike in The Lithuanian Diarchies, have called this system a diarchy, but S.C.Rowell suggests that the nature of this dual rule &quot;...reflects political expediency; it certainly does not meet the formal definition of diarchy as 'rule by two independent authorities'...those two leaders were not equal: the grand duke in Vilnius was supreme&quot;. Rowell, 68.↩

Lukowski and Zawadzki, 33&lt;U+2013&gt;45.↩
Plokhy, 46.↩
