New Cambridge Medieval History, 709&lt;U+2013&gt;712.↩
&quot;Jogaila murdered the stubborn uncle in a quarrel at the end of 1382.&quot; Endre Bojt&lt;U+00E1&gt;r, 181. &quot;Jogaila himself had come to power in 1382 with the murder of his uncle K&lt;U+0119&gt;stutis.&quot; Lukowski and Zawadzki, p 34. Vytautas, during his second Prussian refuge of 1390, was recorded as saying: &quot;Jogaila captured our father and killed him; he also killed our mother and imprisoned me&quot;. Quoted by Mick&lt;U+016B&gt;nait&lt;U+0117&gt;, 157, from a Teutonic chancellery document titled dis ist witoldes sache wedir jagaln und skirgaln. But Sruogien&lt;U+0117&gt;-Sruoga calls the murder &quot;mysterious&quot; and notes that there are &quot;several hypotheses&quot; about what really happened. ''Jogaila (1350&lt;U+2013&gt;1434)''.↩
New Cambridge Medieval History, 709&lt;U+2013&gt;712.↩
Mick&lt;U+016B&gt;nait&lt;U+0117&gt;, 157.↩
The historian John Meyendorff suggests Jogaila may have already been an Orthodox Christian: &quot;In 1377, Olgerd of Lithuania died, leaving the Grand Principality to his son Jagiello, an Orthodox Christian...&quot;. Byzantium and the Rise of Russia, 205. Dmitri, however, made it a condition of the marriage that Jogaila &quot;should be baptized in the Orthodox faith and that he should proclaim his Christianity to all men&quot;. Document quoted by Dvornik, 221.↩
New Cambridge Medieval History, 709&lt;U+2013&gt;712.↩

Jadwiga had actually been crowned king of Poland (rex poloni), because the Polish political system made no provision for a queen regnant. Stone, 8.↩
The nobles of Malopolska, not without suspicion from the nobles of Wielkopolska, made this offer to Jogaila for many reasons. For example, they were &quot;concerned to neutralize the dangers from Lithuania itself and to secure the fertile territories of Halych-Rus'.&quot; Lukowski and Zawadzki, 42. Dvornik suggests that the Polish nobles saw the offer as an &quot;opportunity for increasing their privileges&quot;. Dvornik, 129. They also wished to avoid Austrian influence, Jogaila agreeing to &quot;pay off&quot; Jadwiga's previous fianc&lt;U+00E9&gt; Wilhelm von Habsburg. Lukowski and Zawadzki, 37.↩
New Cambridge Medieval History, 709&lt;U+2013&gt;712.↩
Lukowski and Zawadzki read the clause to imply that &quot;The Kreva Act seemingly promised that he would incorporate Lithuania into Poland.&quot; Lukowski and Zawadzki, 41. Sruogien&lt;U+0117&gt;-Sruoga points out in Jogaila that &quot;Lithuanians probably reasoned that this agreement was only temporary, a kind of wedding formality.&quot; The Kr&lt;U+0117&gt;va Union was short-lived and was succeeded by several other agreements between Lithuania and Poland. According to modern historian G. Rhode, and other researchers, the Kr&lt;U+0117&gt;va Union did not annihilate Lithuanian sovereignty, as interpreted by most Polish historians. G.Rhode. Grundzuge der Geschichte Litauens, 141, 1966. Daniel Z. Stone says, &quot;The exact intent of this union has been hotly debated by historians, but it seems likely that Jogaila and the Poles both intended to unite the realms fully&quot;. Stone, 8.↩
It &quot;reflects the exceptional far-sightedness of the political elites ruling both countries.&quot; K&lt;U+0142&gt;oczowski, 55. It was &quot;a desperate gamble by Jogaila to avert a seemingly inevitable subjugation.&quot; Lukowski and Zawadzki, 38.↩
&quot;...was given the Christian name Vladislovas (Wladyslaw)&quot;. Vanda Sruogien&lt;U+0117&gt;-Sruoga, Jogaila (1350&lt;U+2013&gt;1434). A Slavic name that roughly translates as glorious rule, W&lt;U+0142&gt;adys&lt;U+0142&gt;aw is often Latinised into either Wladislaus or Ladislaus. The choice evoked both W&lt;U+0142&gt;adys&lt;U+0142&gt;aw I of Poland, the Elbow-high, who unified the kingdom a century before, and Saint Ladislaus I of Hungary, a king who sided with the pope against the emperor Henry IV and Christianised Transylvania. New Cambridge Medieval History, 709&lt;U+2013&gt;712.↩
